\begin_layout Section
The Lebesgue Integral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Riemann Integral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

This section is a reading assignment.
 Pay attention to defininition 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the definition of the Riemann Integral.
 Recall
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Dirichlet function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{if }x\in\mathbb{Q}\\
0 & \mbox{if }x\in[0,1]-\mathbb{Q}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
Riemann integrable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists an increasing sequence of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 that are Riemann integrable on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and satisfies 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $|f_{n}|\leq1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 pointwise on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
The Lebesgue Integral of a Bounded Measurable Funcion over a Set of Finite
 Measure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:E\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a simple function, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi:=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}\chi_{_{E_{i}}}\label{eq:canon}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
be the canonical representation, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}$
\end_inset

 are distinct and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}=\{x\in E\mid\varphi(x)=a_{i}\}\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)<\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:E\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a simple function with canonical representation 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:canon})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Define the 
\series bold
Lebesgue integral 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}\varphi=\int_{E}\varphi(x)dx=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}\mu(E_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be the Dirichlet function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{[0,1]}f & =1\cdot\mu\left([0,1]\cap\mathbb{Q}\right)+0\cdot\mu\left([0,1]-\mathbb{Q}\right)\\
 & =1\cdot0+0\cdot1\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)<\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

 be disjoint measurable subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}\chi_{_{E_{i}}}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 are not necessarily distinct.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}\varphi=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}\mu(E_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{a}:=\{x\in E\mid\varphi(x)=a\}=\bigcup_{a_{i}=a}E_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then by finite additivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu(A_{a})=\sum_{a_{i}=a}\mu(E_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}\varphi & =\sum_{a\in\mathbb{R}}a\mu(A_{a})\\
 & =\sum_{a\in\mathbb{R}}a\sum_{a_{i}=a}\mu(E_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}\mu(E_{i}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For the Riemann Integral, we partition the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 For the Lebesgue Integral, we partition the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop2}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 be simple functions defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Linearity) 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}(a\varphi+b\psi)=a\int_{E}\varphi+b\int_{E}\psi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Monotonicity) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\leq\psi$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}\varphi\leq\int_{E}\psi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}\chi_{_{A_{i}}}\qquad\mbox{and}\qquad\psi=\sum_{j=1}^{n}b_{j}\chi_{_{B_{j}}}
\]

\end_inset

be canonical representations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}=\{A_{i}\cap B_{j}\mid A_{i}\cap B_{j}\neq\emptyset,\,1\leq i\le m,\,1\leq j\leq n\}=\{E_{1},\dots,E_{N}\}
\]

\end_inset

 is a disjoint collection whose union is 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi=\sum_{k=1}^{N}c_{k}\chi_{_{E_{k}}}\qquad\mbox{and}\qquad\psi=\sum_{k=1}^{N}d_{k}\chi_{_{E_{k}}}
\]

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\varphi+b\psi=\sum_{k=1}^{N}(ac_{k}+bd_{k})\chi_{_{E_{k}}}
\]

\end_inset

and by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}(a\varphi+b\psi) & =\sum_{k=1}^{N}(ac_{k}+bd_{k})\mu(E_{k})\\
 & =a\int_{E}\varphi+b\int_{E}\psi.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\leq\psi$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta:=\psi-\varphi\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 By linearity, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}\psi-\int_{E}\varphi & =\int_{E}(\psi-\varphi)\\
 & =\int_{E}\eta\\
 & \ge0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}\chi_{_{E_{i}}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

 are measurable with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{i})<\infty$
\end_inset

 but the 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

 are 
\emph on
not necessarily disjoint
\emph default
, then we still have 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We still have monotonicity if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\leq\psi$
\end_inset

 almost everywhere.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be defined and bounded on 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{sup}\left\{ \int_{E}\varphi\mid\varphi\mbox{ is simple, }\varphi\leq f\right\} =\mbox{inf}\left\{ \int_{E}\psi\mid\psi\mbox{ is simple, }\psi\geq f\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 By the Simple Approximation Lemma, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, there exists simple functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{n}\leq f\leq\psi_{n}\mbox{ on }E\mbox{ and }0\leq\psi_{n}-\varphi_{n}\leq\frac{1}{n}.
\]

\end_inset

This implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\int_{E}\psi_{n}-\int_{E}\varphi_{n}\\
 & =\int_{E}(\psi_{n}-\varphi_{n})\\
 & \leq\int_{E}\frac{1}{n}\\
 & =\frac{\mu(E)}{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(\int_{E}\psi_{n}-\int_{E}\varphi_{n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\leq\mbox{inf}\left\{ \int_{E}\psi\mid\psi\mbox{ is simple, }\psi\geq f\right\} -\mbox{sup}\left\{ \int_{E}\varphi\mid\varphi\mbox{ is simple, }\varphi\leq f\right\} \leq\int_{E}\psi_{n}-\int_{E}\varphi_{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and letting 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 proves the stated equality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Omitted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a bounded measurable function defined on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The (
\series bold
Lebesgue
\series default
) 
\series bold
integral 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f:=\mbox{sup}\left\{ \int_{E}\varphi\mid\varphi\mbox{ is simple, }\varphi\leq f\right\} =\mbox{inf}\left\{ \int_{E}\psi\mid\psi\mbox{ is simple, }\psi\geq f\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $E=[a,b]$
\end_inset

, we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}f=\int_{a}^{b}f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E_{1}}f=\int_{E}f\cdot\chi_{_{E_{i}}}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop4}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a bounded function defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx=\int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the lefthand side is the Riemann integral and the righthand side is
 the Lebesgue integral.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since step functions are simple functions, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
LR\int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx & \leq\mbox{sup}\left\{ \int_{a}^{b}\varphi\mid\varphi\mbox{ step function, }\varphi\leq f\right\} \\
 & \leq\mbox{sup}\left\{ \int_{a}^{b}\varphi\mid\varphi\mbox{ is simple, }\varphi\leq f\right\} \\
 & \mbox{\leq inf}\left\{ \int_{a}^{b}\psi\mid\psi\mbox{ is simple, }\psi\geq f\right\} \\
 & \mbox{\leq inf}\left\{ \int_{a}^{b}\psi\mid\psi\mbox{ step function, }\psi\geq f\right\} \\
 & \leq UR\int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $LR$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $UR$
\end_inset

 means lower and upper riemann integral respectively.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable, then all inequalities become equalities and the
 result follows.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $4.2$
\end_inset

 continued
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop7}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of bounded measurable functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 uniformly on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}=\int_{E}f.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then by uniform convergence, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|f_{n}-f|<\frac{\varepsilon}{\mu(E)+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\int_{E}f_{n}-\int_{E}f\right| & =\left|\int_{E}(f_{n}-f)\right|\\
 & \leq\int_{E}\left|f_{n}-f\right|\\
 & \leq\int_{E}\frac{\varepsilon}{\mu(E)+1}\\
 & <\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Prop~(
\backslash
ref{prop7})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, uniform convergence cannot be replaced by pointwise convergence.
 Here's a counterexample: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}:[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{n}(x)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{if }x\geq1/n\\
n & \mbox{if }x<1/n
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to0$
\end_inset

 pointwise, however 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{[0,1]}f_{n} & =\lim_{n\to\infty}1\\
 & =1\\
 & \neq0\\
 & =\int_{[0,1]}0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem8}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Bounded Convergence Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of measurable functions defined on a measurable set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $M\geq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|f_{n}(x)|\leq M$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}(x)\to f(x)$
\end_inset

 pointwise for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}=\int_{E}f.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 be given.
 By Lemma 
\begin_inset Formula $3.10$
\end_inset

 (Lemma to Erogoff's Theorem), there exists a measurable set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 and a number 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E\setminus A)<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|f_{n}(x)-f(x)\right|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\int_{E}f_{n}-\int_{E}f\right| & \leq\int_{E}\left|f_{n}-f\right|\\
 & =\int_{A}\left|f_{n}-f\right|+\int_{E\setminus A}\left|f_{n}-f\right|\\
 & \leq\int_{A}\varepsilon+\int_{E\setminus A}2M\\
 & =\varepsilon\mu(A)+2M\mu(E-A)\\
 & <\varepsilon(\mu(A)+2M)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(A)+2M$
\end_inset

 is a constant, and we are done.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integrals of nonmeasurable functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We make the following notation (not standard): Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{BF}$
\end_inset

 to be the set of bounded measurable functions that vanish outside a set
 of finite measure
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{BF}:=\left\{ h:\mbox{dom}(h)\to\mathbb{R},\mbox{ }h\mbox{ is bounded measurable and }\mu(x\in\mbox{dom}(h)\mid h(x)\neq0)<\infty\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathcal{BF}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}=\{x\in\mbox{\mbox{dom}}(h)\mid h(x)\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{\mbox{dom}(h)}h:=\int_{E}h.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a nonnegative measurable function (not necessarily bounded) defined
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 (not necessarily have finite measure).
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f:=\mbox{sup}\left\{ \int_{E}h\mid h\in\mathcal{BF},\,0\leq h\leq f\mbox{ on }E\right\} \in[0,\infty].
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f\neq\inf_{g\geq f}\int_{E}g
\]

\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 may be unbounded and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}g$
\end_inset

 need not be defined.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop9}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Chebychev's inequality) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a nonnegative measurable function on 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu\left\{ x\in E\mid f(x)\geq\lambda\right\} \leq\frac{1}{\lambda}\int_{E}f
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}:=\{x\in E\mid f(x)\geq\lambda\}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}^{(n)}:=E_{0}\cap[-n,n]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_{0}^{(n)}\}$
\end_inset

 is ascending with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{0}^{(n)}=E.
\]

\end_inset

Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\chi_{_{E_{0}^{(n)}}}\in\mathcal{BF}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\chi_{_{E_{0}^{(n)}}}\leq f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}f & \geq\int_{E}\lambda\chi_{_{E_{0}^{(n)}}}\\
 & =\lambda\int_{E}\chi_{_{E_{0}^{(n)}}}\\
 & =\lambda\mu\left(E_{0}^{(n)}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and letting 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f\geq\lambda\mu(E_{0}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop10}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be measurable.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f=0\quad\iff\quad f=0\mbox{ almost everywhere on }E
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathcal{BF}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq h\leq f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0$
\end_inset

 almost everywhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f=\sup_{\substack{0\leq h\leq f\\
h\in\mathcal{BF}
}
}\int_{E}h=\sup_{\substack{0\leq h\leq f\\
h\in\mathcal{BF}
}
}0=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{+}:=\{x\in E\mid f(x)>0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{+}^{(n)}:=\{x\in E\mid f(x)>1/n\}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{+}=\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{+}^{(n)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So by Chebychev's inequality, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu\left(E_{+}^{(n)}\right)\leq n\int_{E}f=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu(E_{+})\leq\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu\left(E_{+}^{(n)}\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem11}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 be nonnegative measurable functions defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(positive homogenity): 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}cf=c\int_{E}f$
\end_inset

 for all constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c\ge0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(additivity): 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}(f+g)=\int_{E}f+\int_{E}g$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(monotonicity): If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\leq g$
\end_inset

 almost everywhere, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}f\leq\int_{E}g$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Omitted.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Additivity over domain of integration).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be measurable.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are disjoint measurable subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A\cup B}f=\int_{A}f+\int_{B}f.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{0})=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f=\int_{E-E_{0}}f.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Omitted.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Fatou's Lemma) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of nonnegative measurable functions such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}(x)\to f(x)$
\end_inset

 pointwise almost everywhere on a measurable set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f\leq\mbox{liminf}\left(\int_{E}f_{n}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}(x)\to f(x)$
\end_inset

 pointwise everywhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathcal{BF}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\leq f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 vanishes outside 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{h}\subseteq E$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{n}(x):=\min\{h(x),f_{n}(x)\}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{n}(x)\to h(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{h}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is bounded, so are all 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence by the Bounded Convergence Theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}h & =\int_{E_{h}}h\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E_{h}}h_{n}\\
 & \leq\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f=\sup\int_{E}h\leq\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 a.e.
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(F)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 everywhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $E-F$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}f & =\int_{E-F}f+\int_{F}f\\
 & =\int_{E-F}f\\
 & \leq\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E-F}f_{n}\\
 & \leq\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This completes the proof.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The example following Prop 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 shows that strict inequality may hold.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem14}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Monotone Convergence Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be an increasing sequence of nonnegative measurable functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\lim_{n\to\infty}f_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 a.e.
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f=\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By Fataou's Lemma, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{E}f\leq\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}.\label{eq:1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theorem11})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{E}f_{n}\leq\int_{E}f\qquad\implies\qquad\lim\int_{E}f_{n}\leq\int_{e}f\label{eq:2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 proves the theorem.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor15}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Interchanging 
\begin_inset Formula $\int$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum$
\end_inset

) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a given sequence of nonnegative measurable functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}u_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\int_{E}u_{n}
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}:=\sum_{k=1}^{n}u_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is increasing.
 Hence by the Monotone Convergence Theorem,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}f & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}\sum_{k=1}^{n}u_{k}\\
 & \leq\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=1}^{n}\int_{E}u_{k}\\
 & \leq\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\int_{E}u_{k}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A nonnegative measure for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
integrable 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f<\infty.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop16}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g:E\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be measurable functions.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g\leq f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}(f-g)=\int_{E}f-\int_{E}g.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\infty & >\int_{E}f\\
 & =\int_{E}((f-g)+g)\\
 & =\int_{E}(f-g)+\int_{E}g
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}g<\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}(f-g)-\int_{E}f-\int_{E}g$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is integrable and equality in the proposition holds.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be measurable.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is finite a.e.
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then by Chebychev's inequality, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left\{ x\in E\mid f(x)=\infty\right\}  & \leq\mu\left\{ x\in E\mid f(x)\geq n\right\} \\
 & \leq\frac{1}{n}\int_{E}f.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}f$
\end_inset

 is finite, letting 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left\{ x\in E\mid f(x)=\infty\right\} =0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem18}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Beppo Levi's Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}:E\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be an increasing sequence of nonnegative measurable functions.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\int_{E}f_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 converges pointwise to a measurable function on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 that is finite a.e.
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}=\int_{E}f<\infty.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Omitted.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x):=\lim_{n\to\infty}f_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 and use Monotone Convergence Theorem.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The General Lebesgue Integral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that for 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to[-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}(x):=\max\{f(x),0\}$
\end_inset

 is the positive part of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-}(x):=\max\{-f(x),0\}$
\end_inset

 is the negative part of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=f^{+}-f^{-},\qquad|f|=f^{+}+f^{-}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-f)^{+}=f^{-}\qquad(-f)^{-}=f^{+}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop19}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to[-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be measurable.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-}$
\end_inset

 are integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $|f|$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-}$
\end_inset

 are integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}|f| & =\int_{E}(f^{+}+f^{-})\\
 & =\int_{E}f^{+}+\int_{E}f^{-}\\
 & <\infty
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|f|$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $|f|$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq f^{+}\leq|f|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq f^{-}\leq|f|$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}f^{+}\leq\int_{E}|f|<\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}f^{-}\leq\int_{E}|f|<\infty$
\end_inset

 by monotonicity.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to[-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be measurable.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
integrable 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $|f|$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 (equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-}$
\end_inset

 are integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

).
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f:=\int_{E}f^{+}-\int_{E}f^{-}\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop20}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to[-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is finite a.e.
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f=\int_{E-E_{0}}f
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
if 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{0})=0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is integrable, 
\begin_inset Formula $|f|$
\end_inset

 is integrable, thererefore 
\begin_inset Formula $|f|$
\end_inset

 is finite a.e.
 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop17})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is finite a.e.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}f & =\int_{E}f^{+}-\int_{E}f^{-}\\
 & =\int_{E-E_{0}}f^{+}-\int_{E-E_{0}}f^{-}\\
 & =\int_{E-E_{0}}f.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop21}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Integral Comparison Test).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to[-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be measurable.
 Suppose there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $g:E\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|f|\leq g$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\int_{E}f\right|\leq\int_{E}|f|.\label{eq:absconv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{absconv})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 holds for all integrable 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 (Replace 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $|f|$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}|f|\leq\int_{E}g<\infty$
\end_inset

 by monotonicity, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\int_{E}f\right| & =\left|\int_{E}f^{+}-\int_{E}f^{-}\right|\\
 & \leq\left|\int_{E}f^{+}\right|+\left|\int_{E}f^{-}\right|\\
 & \leq\int_{E}f^{+}+\int_{E}f^{-}\\
 & =\int_{E}|f|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem22}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g:E\to[-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $cf$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}cf=c\int_{E}f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f+g$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}(f+g)=\int_{E}f+\int_{E}g$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f\leq g$
\end_inset

 a.e.
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{E}f\leq\int_{E}g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Omitted.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor23}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Additivity over domain of integration).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to[-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 are disjoint and measurable, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A\cup B}f=\int_{A}f+\int_{B}f.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Omitted.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem24}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Lebesgue Dominated Convergence Theorem).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of measurable functions such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 pointwise a.e.
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists an integrable function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|f_{n}|\leq g$
\end_inset

 pointwise everywhere on a.e.
 all 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f=\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is integrable since 
\begin_inset Formula $|f_{n}|\leq g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|f|\leq g$
\end_inset

 implies integrability of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $|f_{n}|\leq g$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $-g\leq f_{n}\leq g$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $g-f_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g+f_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Applying Fatou's Lemma to 
\begin_inset Formula $g-f_{n}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}(g-f) & \leq\mbox{liminf}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}(g-f_{n})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}g-\int_{E}f & \leq\mbox{liminf}_{n\to\infty}(\int_{E}g-\int_{E}f_{n})\\
 & \leq\int_{E}g-\mbox{liminf}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{E}f\geq\mbox{limsup}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}.\label{eq:limsup}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Repeating the process for 
\begin_inset Formula $g+f_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{E}(g+f) & \leq\mbox{liminf}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}(g+f_{n})\nonumber \\
\int_{E}g+\int_{E}f & \leq\mbox{liminf}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}g+\int_{E}f_{n}\nonumber \\
 & =\int_{E}g+\mbox{liminf}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}\nonumber \\
\int_{E}f & \leq\mbox{liminf}_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}\label{eq:liminf}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:limsup})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:liminf})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 proves the theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem25}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (General Lebesgue Dominated Convergence Theorem).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\{g_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of nonnegative measurable functions that converge a.e.
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 to an integrable function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of measurable functions such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|f_{n}|\leq g_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 a.e.
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}g_{n}=\int_{E}g<\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f=\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Exercise.
 Note that setting 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}=g$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 implies Lebesgue Dominated Convergence Theorem.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Countable Additivity over Domain of Integration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem26}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to[-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a disjoint countable collection of measurable subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}=E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E}f=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\int_{E_{n}}f.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem2}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This generalizes 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{cor23})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}:=\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}E_{k}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}:=f\cdot\chi_{_{U}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a measurable function on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|f_{n}|\leq|f|$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 pointwise on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, by Lebesgue Dominated Convergence Theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{E}f & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f_{n}\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{E}f\cdot\chi_{_{U_{n}}}\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{U_{n}}f\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=1}^{n}\int_{E_{k}}f\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\int_{E_{k}}f.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
Vitali cover 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $I\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(I)<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{1}:=\left\{ [x-1/n,x+1/n]\mid x\in[0,1],\,n\in\mathbb{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a Vitali cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, however 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{I}}=\left\{ [x-1,x+1]\mid x\in[0,1]\right\} $
\end_inset

 is not a Vitali cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma2.5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Vitali Cover Lemma) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{\star}(E)<\infty$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 be a Vitali cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 consisting of intervals.
 Then given 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there exists finite disjoint subcollection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{I_{1},\dots,I_{N}\}\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu^{\star}\left(E\setminus\bigcup_{n=1}^{N}I_{n}\right)>\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Omitted.
 Selection process for the subcollection: Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{I_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 inductively as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 be arbitrary.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{n}$
\end_inset

 have been chosen.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{n}:=\sup\left\{ \ell(I)\mid I\in\mathcal{I},\,I\cap\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}I_{k}\right)=\emptyset\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}I_{k}$
\end_inset

, we are done.
 Otherwise choose 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n+1}\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(I_{n+1})>k_{n}/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n+1}\cap\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}I_{k}\right)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn2}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:E\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

.
 Define the 
\series bold
derivatives 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $D^{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{+}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{+}f(x)=\mbox{limsup}_{h\to0^{+}}\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}\quad\mbox{and}\quad D_{+}f(x)=\mbox{liminf}_{h\to0}\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the 
\series bold
derivatives 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $D^{-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{-}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{-}f(x)=\mbox{limsup}_{h\to0^{+}}\frac{f(x)-f(x-h)}{h}\quad\mbox{and}\quad D_{-}f(x)=\mbox{liminf}_{h\to0}\frac{f(x)-f(x-h)}{h}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
differentiable 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{+}f(x)=D_{+}f(x)=D^{-}f(x)=D_{-}f(x)\neq\pm\infty.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, the common value is called the 
\series bold
derivative 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a 
\series bold
right-hand derivative
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x_{+})$
\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{+}f(x)=D_{+}f(x)\neq\pm\infty
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a 
\series bold
left-hand derivative
\series default
, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{1}(x_{-})$
\end_inset

, if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{-}f(x)=D_{-}f(x)\neq\pm\infty
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop2.8}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 and one of its derivatives is everywhere greater than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is nondecreasing on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem27}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be an increasing (or decreasing) real-valued function on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable a.e.
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 and the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f'$
\end_inset

 is measurable.
 Moreover, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}f'(x)dx\leq f(b)-f(a)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is increasing,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}f'(x)dx\geq f(b)-f(a)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is decreasing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The inequality does not hold in general.
 Here's a counterexample: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x):[0,1]\to\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{if }x\in[0,1/2]\\
1 & \mbox{if }x\in(1/2,1].
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}f'(x)dx=0$
\end_inset

, however 
\begin_inset Formula $f(1)-f(0)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Even if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous, the reverse inequality need not hold.
 A counterexample in this case is given by the Cantor function.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Question 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

: What kind of functions are differentiable a.e?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Question 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset


\series default
: When do these equalities hold? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Functions of bounded variation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:[a,b]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\{x_{i}\}_{i=0}^{k}$
\end_inset

 be a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a=x_{0}<x_{1}<\cdots<x_{k}=b$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $p=p(\mathcal{P})=\sum_{i=1}^{k}(f(x_{i})-f(x_{i-1}))^{+}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=n(\mathcal{P})=\sum_{i=1}^{k}(f(x_{i})-f(x_{i-1}))^{-}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t(\mathcal{P})=n+p=\sum_{i=1}^{k}|f(x_{i})-f(x_{i-1})|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $P=P_{a}^{b}(f)=\sup_{\mathcal{P}}(p),$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N=N_{a}^{b}(f)=\sup_{\mathcal{P}}(n),$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T=T_{a}^{b}(f)=\sup_{\mathcal{P}}(t).$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $P,N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 are the 
\series bold
positive
\series default
, 
\series bold
negative
\series default
, and 
\series bold
total variations 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $T<\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is said to be of 
\series bold
bounded variation 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in BV([a,b])$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
x\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2x}\right) & \mbox{if }0<x\leq1\\
0 & \mbox{if }x=0.
\end{cases}\begin{aligned}x\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2x}\right) & \mbox{if }0<x\leq1\\
0 & \mbox{if }x=0.
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous but is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
of bounded variation.
 Proof: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n}=\left\{ 0,\frac{1}{2n},\frac{1}{2n-1},\dots,\frac{1}{3},\frac{1}{2},1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $t(\mathcal{P}_{n})=V(f,\mathcal{P}_{n})=1+\frac{1}{2}+\cdots+\frac{1}{n}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}^{1}(f)=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem4}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f(b)-f(a)=p-n=\sum_{i=1}^{k}(f(x_{i})-f(x_{i-1}))$
\end_inset

 is a telescoping sum.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is increasing, then 
\begin_inset Formula $TV(f)=f(b)-f(a)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\max\{P,N\}\leq T\leq P+N$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T & =\sup_{\mathcal{P}}(t)\\
 & =\sup_{\mathcal{P}}(p+n)\\
 & \le\sup_{\mathcal{P}}(p)+\sup_{\mathcal{P}}(n)\\
 & =P+N.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma4.5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in BV([a,b])$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f(b)-f(a)=P_{a}^{b}-N_{a}^{b}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $T_{a}^{b}=P_{a}^{b}+N_{a}^{b}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Remark~(
\backslash
ref{rem4})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=n+f(b)-f(a)$
\end_inset

, Taking the supremum over all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P=N+f(b)-f(a)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f(b)-f(a)=P-N$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=p+n=2p-(f(b)-f(a))$
\end_inset

.
 Taking supremum over all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $T=2P-(P-N)=P+N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem5.5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Lemma 5 and Jordan's Theorem) 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in BV([a,b])$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the difference of two monotone real-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in BV([a,b])$
\end_inset

 and define 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x):=P_{a}^{x}(f)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x):=N_{a}^{x}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 are increasing and real valued.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\le P_{a}^{x}\leq T_{a}^{x}\leq T_{a}^{b}<\infty,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\le N_{a}^{x}\leq T_{a}^{x}\leq T_{a}^{b}<\infty,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma4.5})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)-(h(x)-f(a))$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a difference of two monotone functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g-h$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 both monotone, say decreasing (other cases are the same).
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\{x_{i}\}_{i=0}^{k}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
t & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}|f(x_{i})-f(x_{i-1})|\\
 & \leq\sum_{i=1}^{n}|g(x_{i})-g(x_{i-1})|+\sum_{i=1}^{n}|h(x_{i})-h(x_{i-1})|\\
 & \leq g(a)-g(b)+h(a)-h(b)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
implies 
\begin_inset Formula $T<\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in BV([a,b])$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor6}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in BV([a,b])$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

 exists a.e.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\sin(1/x)\notin BV([0,1])$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

 exists a.e.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
